1 21–803.
2 (a) (1) Except as provided in paragraphs (3) through (5) of this subsection, if,
3 on the basis of an engineering and traffic investigation, a local authority determines that
4 any maximum speed limit specified in this subtitle is greater or less than reasonable or
5 safe under existing conditions on any part of a highway in its jurisdiction, it may establish
6 a reasonable and safe maximum speed limit for that part of the highway, which may:
7 (i) Decrease the limit at an intersection;
8 (ii) Increase the limit in an urban district to not more than 50 miles
9 per hour;
10 (iii) Decrease the limit in an urban district; or
11 (iv) Decrease the limit outside an urban district to not less than 25
12 miles per hour.
13 (4) (i) This paragraph applies only to:
14 1. Anne Arundel County and Montgomery County; and
15 2. Municipalities located in Anne Arundel County and
16 Montgomery County.
17 (ii) 1. [A] SUBJECT TO SUBSUBPARAGRAPH 2 OF THIS
18 SUBPARAGRAPH, A local authority may decrease the maximum speed limit to not less than
19 15 miles per hour on a highway only after performing an engineering and traffic
20 investigation.
21 2. IN MONTGOMERY COUNTY, A LOCAL AUTHORITY MAY
22 DECREASE THE MAXIMUM SPEED LIMIT ON A HIGHWAY UNDER SUBSUBPARAGRAPH
23 1 OF THIS SUBPARAGRAPH WITHOUT PERFORMING AN ENGINEERING AND TRAFFIC
24 INVESTIGATION.
25 (iii) A local authority may not implement a new speed monitoring
26 system to enforce speed limits on any portion of a highway for which the speed limit has
27 been decreased under this paragraph.
28 (c) An altered maximum speed limit established under this section is effective
29 when posted on appropriate signs giving notice of the limit.
30 (d) Except in Baltimore City, any alteration by a local authority of a maximum
31 speed limit on a part or extension of a State highway is not effective until it is approved by
32 the State Highway Administration.

